Heres the rest of my review: (had to split it up because Epi doesnt like long reviews) 6. You dont want to transfer the hot pumpkin out of its baking dish to serve it, so bake it in a pretty baking dish or pyrex pie plate. The pumpkin skin isnt exciting to eat (though its probably edible) so diners will need knife and fork to eat this dish. 7. I do recommend making croutons of the bread, instead of slices. I layered croutons and cheeses and then poured liquid in until it was just showing near the top. Leave a little room to expand at the top  the filling will puff up and get brown on top after you remove the top of the pumpkin. 8. The dish works better with pumpkins at least 4  5 pounds in size. A really small pumpkin (like to serve only hubby and me) has a very small cavity which makes it difficult to fill. 9. Amounts for a 4-5 pound pumpkin: no more than one baguette (probably less), 2  2.5 cups of grated cheese and 2 - 2.5 cups of liquid. Two of these easily served 16 women as main dish at a luncheon, with salad and bread, (and appetizers and dessert). 10. Overall, this is a festive fall dish that makes a dramatic presentation for a special occasion and it was successful for my daughters shower . The filling is yummy but even though I used sugar pumpkins from a local farm stand, the pumpkin didnt have a lot of flavor, so I ended up rating it only a three.

