Here's the rest of my advice (Epi doesn't like long reviews, so I had to split mine into two parts!) 6. You dont want to transfer the hot pumpkin out of its baking dish to serve it, so bake it in a pretty baking dish or pyrex pie plate. The pumpkin skin isnt exciting to eat (though its probably edible) so diners will need knife and fork to eat this dish. 7. I do recommend making croutons of the bread, instead of slices. I layered croutons and cheeses and then poured liquid in until it was just showing near the top. Leave a little room to expand at the top  the filling will puff up and get brown on top after you remove the top of the pumpkin. 8. The dish works better with pumpkins at least 4  5 pounds in size. A really small pumpkin (like to serve only hubby and me) has a very small cavity which makes it difficult to fill. 9. Amounts for a 4-5 pound pumpkin: no more than one baguette (probably less), 2  2.5 cups of grated cheese and 2 - 2.5 cups of liquid. Two of these easily served 16 women as main dish at a luncheon, with salad and bread, (and appetizers and dessert). 10. Overall, this is a festive fall dish that makes a dramatic presentation for a special occasion and it was successful for my daughters shower . The filling is yummy but even though I used sugar pumpkins from a local farm stand, the pumpkin didnt have a lot of flavor, so I ended up rating it only a three.

Rating: 3
I made this dish twice experimentally, then served it over Thanksgiving-weekend at my vegetarian daughters baby shower. Here's what I learned: 1. It can be bland, so use liberal amounts of salt, garlic and nutmeg for flavor, and maybe other things (the suggestions for carmelized shallots and cayenne pepper have appeared in reviews since I last checked the site  Id use one or both ideas next time. Also might try adding crumbled cooked bacon if not making it for vegetarians.) 2. Dont substitute for the heavy cream  you need it for flavor. 3. The main flavor comes from the cheese, so choose well. I used Gruyere and Jarlsberg because my store didnt have any Emmental. 4. Do substitute white wine for some (maybe even all) of the broth 5. It is crucial for the pumpkin to get fully cooked, but its hard to check for doneness because if you poke into it, some of the liquidy filling runs out the hole. You can press on the side of the pumpkin with the back of a large spoon to see if its tender. Also look for the burnished color of the pumpkin. If it has not turned darker in color, it definitely is not done yet. I used sugar pumpkins, approx 4 to 5 lbs each, and pre-cooked them in the microwave for five minutes after they were hollowed out, but before I stuffed them. After stuffing them, I baked them at 425 for an hour and a quarter  with tops removed for the last 45 minutes, and even then one of the three was not as done as I would have liked. I would not recommend lowering the temperature at all.

