Rating: 4
This came out fantastic for me with a few modifications. The purists among you may complain, but the dish really was superb and in my view these were only minor changes which enhanced the recipe. I substituted a Pinot Grigio for half of the stock, and as I'm not keen on soggy bread, I used a day old baguette to make large garlic croutons instead of just toasted bread. I tossed chunks cut from the baguette with olive oil, crushed garlic and a little salt before toasting them in the oven. My pumpkin was smaller than called for (about the size of your average honeydew melon), so I roasted at 325 for a little more than an hour and increased the temp at the end to maybe 375. I took inspiration from kstancik and took the 'lid' off for the last 20 minutes or so and the top layers browned nicely (the lid came out really nutty and tasty too). I served it up by letting it rest a few moments, then cutting large wedges which I was able to spoon into wide bowls. Really pretty coming out of the oven, and in the bowls. The garlic and wine really worked well to bring out the 'fondue' flavours from the filling and the pumpkin was lovely, tender and hearty. Perfect early winter meal!

